Side note: these weren't the only aspects of kana spelling that were reformed after WWII. There used to be tons of rules that made kana spelling almost as annoying as English spelling  When you look up a word in a J-J dictionary, it still tells you the old kana spelling. https://t.co/v0x0YVZKjj

This continued all the way up until after WWII, when kana was completely reformed to make spelling straightforward  So, if you pick up a book published in 1940, やっている will be written as やつてゐる (but was pronounced the exact same as やっている)

Overtime, these sounds shifted and eventually became pronounced the same as い and え. BUT, things that were ORIGINALLY pronounced as wi" and "we" continued to be written with ゐ and ゑ  It's similar to how we still write "knife"
null: even though we no longer pronounce the "k" sound"

tweet_content: Turns out it's more common for Japanese learners to not know about ゐ and ゑ at all!  Here's an explanation:  When kana was created ~1000 years ago, the sounds wi" and "we" were a common part of Japanese
null: and they were written with ゐ and ゑ https://t.co/4hk3H47omo"

tweet_content: It's funny how many Japanese learners think that ゐ is pronounced wi" and ゑ "we"
null: when in reality up until WWII both these characters were used constantly and were simply pronounced exactly the same as い and え https://t.co/ulKNFnlqWG"

It would be interesting to see how various NFT marketplaces compete (not on liquidity) but on the ease of onboarding new users.   Do check out my article if you are keen to read more: https://t.co/elrDwTk1c6  Thank you for reading! ✨

What does this war show us?  🔹Each NFT marketplace needs to decide what is their niche: what type of users they want on its platform.   🔹No one is really too big to go up against in the Web3 space. We are early!   🔹Users benefit either way because of friendly competition.

However, creating incentives that purely encourage volume is unwise as this will just result in wash trading (eg. LooksRare where an estimated $8b of wash trade is said to be generated making up the vast majority of its sales as users attempt to game the trading rewards model)

3⃣ Incentivize existing and new users  Anyone looking to build a product in the Web3 space has to build with a community first" mindset.   Different strategies need to be implemented for diff groups of users in order to command more usage and trading vol."

Factors such as allocation structure as well as a long-term strategy should be considered.   If the intention is to IPO, perhaps it does not make sense to create tokens as it will create more problems when it comes to regulations.

2⃣ Airdrop Tokens?  After $BLUR was airdropped to users, volume increased on BLUR as majority are attempting to bid for for S2.   However, simply creating tokens and giving them to users is not so straightforward. https://t.co/OF1YvAQD0g
So how can other marketplaces compete?  1⃣ Stable platform  Be honest, how many times have you encountered Oops
null: something went wrong" page?  Users want to be able to access information easily
accurately and in real time."

2）Owange Boy的Web3之旅(續)：  像是我就非常喜歡這幅由@MindblowonNFT 的畫家@lickpalik 合作的，但這些都是少量製作。為了讓更多的人認識與擁有OwangeBoy最新作品@owangenft系列，將於2022年11月面世。 https://t.co/x8pT9i1JDi
2）Owange Boy的Web3之旅(續)：  在2022年2月的 Kong又與其他藝術家朋友合作了𝗢𝘄𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲𝗕𝗼𝘆 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗙𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘀 (https://t.co/p2kGvhcjWt) 由不同的藝術家打造出不同風格的OwangeBoy，當中也包含了不少大家耳熟能詳的項目畫家。
2）Owange Boy的Web3之旅：  十多年來Owange boy已經是一個成功的IP，受到了許多人的喜愛。 因此Kong決定將Owange進一步發展成為一個能夠把快樂傳播到世界的品牌。所以在2021年9月發表了第一個Owange的Web3項目𝗢𝘄𝗮𝗻𝗴𝗲 𝗧𝗲𝗮𝗺 𝗣𝗙𝗣 𝗖𝗼𝗹𝗹𝗲𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗯𝗹𝗲𝘀 (https://t.co/FuSEDipNqv)
1）關於藝術家：  Kong Andri是著名的平面設計師和玩具藝術家，在2011年，Kong看見了日本海嘯帶給人的災難與痛苦，為了幫助海嘯災民，他創作了OwangeBoy這個角色來帶給人們快樂。OwangeBoy的靈感來源於Kong的兒子與小時候看過的日本與美國動漫。相關作品有平面畫作與實體玩具！ https://t.co/JwQyRmHPAW

[9] A complete boat tour around the historical city takes about an hour without stopping. We started the tour at the Station Pier (https://t.co/l5GOUuDKq1) but we had to telephone to arrange that. The real pier is opposite Chantharakasem National Museum (https://t.co/koueO1wlaP). https://t.co/tJMRgVBiPN

[8] Our third and last stop on the boat tour was at Wat Chaiwatthanaram. The temple was built in 1630 by King Prasat Thong. It has a 35-meter-high prang. This is a popular location for Thais to dress up in period clothes to take photos.  📍MAP: https://t.co/zPkwTIPcIO #Thailand https://t.co/VBUe3wlSaM

[7] There are no fixed stops during the boat tour. If somewhere takes your fancy and there’s a pier, you can stop there. Our second stop was Wat Phutthaisawan. The highlight is the Khmer-style Prang which is surrounded by many smaller pagodas.   📍MAP: https://t.co/JzCXZHcV61 https://t.co/X8mRp10iTO

[6] The first stop on our boat tour was Wat Phanan Choeng Worawihan. It was founded shortly before the establishment of Ayutthaya as the capital. Its main building enshrines a huge, seated Buddha image, that is 17 meters tall.   📍MAP: https://t.co/vE8LhroCeg #Thailand https://t.co/Ky5PqkZyr3

[5] We rented the long-tailed boat through the Facebook page of Tippawan Boat (https://t.co/vHp4J123X1). The cost was 700 Baht for the complete loop around the old city plus 100 Baht per stop. We did three stops and so it was 1,000 Baht. They picked us up at the station pier. https://t.co/shfPF7QM48

[4] When the train arrives in Ayutthaya you need to work out what you want to do next as the this train ticket doesn’t include a tour. Options include Tuk Tuk tour, bicycle or motorcycle rentals, or even a boat which is what I decided I wanted to do. https://t.co/60Ua1dkupg

😷 Chiang Mai is presently the most polluted city in the world as the air quality is classed as “unhealthy”. In the neighbouring provinces of Chiang Rai and Mae Hong Son, on the border with Laos and Myanmar, it is far worse as it is presently “hazardous” to your health. #Thailand https://t.co/t3I5CrSFCz

😷 If you plan on visiting Northern Thailand, in particular Chiang Rai or Pai in Mae Hong Son, you will need a full face gas mask as the air quality continues to be “hazardous”. However it’s not fair to blame it all on Thai farmers. Laos and Myanmar are just as bad. #Thailand https://t.co/fr2az8lR8C
[3] Guide to Steam Train Excursions in Thailand – Thai Train Guide https://t.co/E5gzxWUqiJ  #RailTourism #Trains #Thailand https://t.co/5OStX47YmM

[2] There are six steam train trips a year on important dates. They go to three different locations: Ayutthaya, Chachoengsao and Nakhon Pathom. Tickets are 299 Baht for 3rd Class (8 carriages) and 799 Baht for 1st Class (2 carriages). https://t.co/qMV0AXjIv3

🚂 Good morning from Hua Lamphong Station. Today is the 126th anniversary of the opening of the first railway in #Thailand and the founding of the State Railway of Thailand on 26th March 1897.   This is a live THREAD of my steam train trip to Ayutthaya.  #RailTourism #Thailand https://t.co/WacG7chx89

🚂 Are you taking the steam train to Ayutthaya on Sunday? Here is my photo blog to give you some ideas of what you can do. At the station you can rent bicycles or hire a Tuk Tuk for a tour.   ✅ Steam Train Trip to Ayutthaya https://t.co/ujc96BoUfA  #RailTourism #Thailand

Rare photo opportunity tomorrow morning at Bangkok Railway Station (Hua Lamphong) as there will be four steam locomotives there. Two of them will be taking passengers to Ayutthaya.  ✅ Guide to the Steam Train Trip to Ayutthaya https://t.co/GIz338TrsR  #RailTourism #Thailand
🎥 126th anniversary celebrations for the State Railway of Thailand at Hua Lamphong Railway Station this weekend until 10pm on Sunday #Bangkok #Thailand https://t.co/DcfAHwKIk7
🎥 3D projection mapping on the front of Hua Lamphong Railway Station at 7:00pm and 8:00pm today and Sunday.   #Bangkok #Thailand https://t.co/MvmoZ3IfrA

[10] This concludes the day trip to Ayutthaya onboard the #KiHa183 train. I hope you enjoyed my photos and I’ve inspired you to try this train on a future trip. There are now excursions every weekend.  ✅ Explore Thailand onboard the Kiha-183 Train https://t.co/yIote6aozI https://t.co/5qMEVUs1uF

[9] The final stop, and the highlight for me, was the royal waiting room at Bang Pa-In Railway Station. This was officially opened on 26th March 1896 by King Rama V. It’s not normally open to the public and we were lucky to be able to go inside.  #Thailand https://t.co/HVU7BNl1AQ

[8] Our next stop was at Kong Khong Market in Bang Pa-In district. I have been here a few times and I do like it. But really it’s only interesting if you are hungry. And I was still full from lunch.  📍MAP: https://t.co/AcQcz9UdhO   #Thailand https://t.co/0q390bFOkD

[7] I love doing boat trips. These are always a highlight of any trip that I do. If you come here by yourself it is possible to rent a small boat for around 700 Baht. The old city of Ayutthaya is built on an island and taking a boat ride is a good way to see some of the sights. https://t.co/nqOPcWotlm

[6] We had a buffet lunch at a local hotel which was included in the tour price. We then went back on the bus to go a short distance to a pier where we boarded a converted rice barge for a tour along the river.   #Thailand https://t.co/IvoaCdKj4G

[5] Our first stop was at Chao Sam Phraya National Museum. The admission price is included in the tour price. The highlight is the new Gold Treasure Exhibition that contains more than 2,000 gold artefacts found in the crypts at Wat Ratchaburana and Wat Mahathat.  #Thailand https://t.co/Mcm9vlblcD

[4] The train arrived at Ayutthaya Railway Station at 9:50am which is where we switched to buses for the first part of the tour. This is what makes these trips worthwhile as they include both the train and local transport at the destination.  #Thailand https://t.co/UWoukDqHJM

It’s good to see the British Embassy being proactive when it comes to tourist safety in #Thailand. But really it’s the job of Thai authorities to make sure motorbikes are not rented to tourists who don’t have a license or the proper insurance and the police to enforce laws. https://t.co/MzFx6hDUm1

[3] Our trip today is to Ayutthaya. The ticket cost is 1,499 Baht and includes breakfast, lunch, bus and boat tours, and souvenirs. The price of other tours might vary. Sometimes cheaper sometimes more expensive.  #RailTourism #Thailand https://t.co/ORFKLfCiJn

[2] To buy tickets for the #KiHa183 excursion train, go to the D-Ticket website https://t.co/w1hE9XECqw and click on ‘Exploring Thailand by Train’. There’s a different destination every week. Call 1690 for more information. https://t.co/KSIenOqZld

Good morning from Hua Lamphong Station. Today I’m on the #Kiha183 excursion train to Ayutthaya. This is a live THREAD 🧵 about this trip.   Follow @ThaiTrainGuide for more information on the trains.   #RailTourism #Thailand https://t.co/EVc62yA2Gl

Last chance this weekend to attend the activities at Hua Lamphong Station. The highlight is the special lighting from 7:00pm to 10:00pm. But don’t miss the projection mapping on the front of the building. There are two rounds. 7:00pm and 8:00pm. Each round lasts for ten minutes. https://t.co/7fvc9PcFWg

The scammers are still at work at Hua Lamphong station. (When I first came to Thailand I was scammed by them. They told me the train was full and took me to a nearby travel agency to buy a bus ticket.)  As soon as they saw me taking pictures, they ran off to hide.  #BangkokScams https://t.co/mONygNtmC2

Good morning from Bangkok Railway Station. Another day, another train trip.  Many people asked me if Hua Lamphong is closed. It’s not. Only the long distance trains moved to Krung Thep Aphiwat. You still come here for the tourist trains, Eastern Line trains, and commuter trains. https://t.co/tvuBmKjGE1
